The [[Right Reverend|Rt Rev]]''' Peter Sorenson Royston''' was a [[Bishop of Mauritius]].<ref>[[Who's Who (UK)|”Who was Who 1897-1990”]] London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref>

Born in [[London]] on 6 June 1830 and educated at [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul’s]] and  [[Trinity College, Cambridge]],<ref>{{acad|id=RSTN849PS|name=Royston, Peter Sorensón}}</ref> he was ordained in 1853<ref>"The Clergy List, Clerical Guide and Ecclesiastical Directory" London, Hamilton & Co 1889</ref> and began his career as a [[Tutor|Resident Tutor]]  at the [[Church Mission Society|Church Missionary College]] in [[London]].  After that he was the [[Vicar|incumbent]] of the [[Church Mission Society|CMS]] [[Chapel]], [[Madras]] and then of St Thomas’, [[Mauritius]].<ref>[http://www.bestofmauritius.net/Christian%20Churches%20%20Mauritius.htm Church details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090628155726/http://www.bestofmauritius.net/Christian%20Churches%20%20Mauritius.htm |date=28 June 2009 }}</ref> He was [[Bishop]] of the [[Mauritius|country]] from 1872<ref>[[The Times]], Friday, Nov 22, 1872; pg. 5; Issue 27541; col B ''Ecclesiastical Intelligence New Bishop of Mauritius''</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8xPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA158 |chapter=Mauritius |title=Colonial Office List for 1886 |location=London }}</ref> to 1891 when he resigned through ill health.<ref>[[The Times]], Tuesday, Feb 10, 1891; pg. 6; Issue 33244; col C ''Ecclesiastical Intelligence Bishop of Mauritius to resign''</ref> Afterwards, an [[Assistant Bishop]] within the [[Anglican Diocese of Liverpool|Diocese of Liverpool]]<ref>[http://archives.lambethpalacelibrary.org.uk:8080/Archives/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo=='MSS/1772') National Church Institutions Database of Manuscripts and Archives]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  he died on 28 January  1915 at [[Worthing]].

